<p>
  <span class="post-opener"
    >I still remember reading this story when I was a kid.</span
  >
  It stayed with me, and I come back to it every time I catch myself adding
  up what I already have instead of asking what it could become.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p>So how much is a pound of copper worth, after all?</p>
<p>
  Many years ago, a father said to his son: &ldquo;Right now we have no
  possessions; our only wealth is wisdom. When other people answer that
  1 + 1 = 2, you should think 1 + 1 &gt; 2.&rdquo; The son listened and
  nodded seriously.
</p>
<p>
  Later, against the odds, the father and son survived and started over.
</p>
<p>
  In 1946, the father brought his son to the city of Houston, in the United
  States, to trade in copper goods. One day the father called his son over
  and asked, &ldquo;Do you know how much a pound of copper is worth?&rdquo;
  The boy answered with certainty, &ldquo;35 cents.&rdquo; The father said,
  &ldquo;That is not wrong. Today everyone in the state of Texas knows that a
  pound of copper costs 35 cents. But you should know that a pound of copper
  is worth more than 35 cents. Try taking this pound of copper and making a
  door handle out of it.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
  Just as his father had taught him, he did not only make door handles from
  copper, but also the springs for Swiss watches and the medals for the
  Olympic Games. He once sold a pound of copper for 3,500 dollars. In 1974,
  the government began calling on companies and organizations to clear away
  the scrap at the foot of the Statue of Liberty. But several months went by,
  and no company was willing to take the job. After hearing this news, he
  immediately went and signed a contract with the government, and set to work
  at once: he melted down the leftover copper and cast it into small Statues
  of Liberty; the mud and rotten wood he worked into bases for the statue;
  the lead and aluminum he made into keys and sold widely on the market; and
  even the dust on the statue, he had people scrape it off and sold it to
  flower growers.
</p>
<p>
  After three months, he had turned that pile of scrap into 3.5 million
  dollars, so the value of each pound of copper had risen ten thousand times
  over. By now he was no longer the &ldquo;foolish&rdquo; boy of years past,
  but had become the chairman of the board of the McCall company.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p>
  So how much is a pound of copper worth, after all? From the example above,
  we can understand that true value does not lie in the object itself, but in
  how well a person knows how to use their mind and wisdom to make use of
  that object.
</p>
<p>
  It is worth teaching our children from an early age that true wealth is
  wisdom, and that wisdom alone can never be taken away by anyone. It is a
  clear-sighted way to raise a child, and it is borne out by the example
  above: when everyone believes that 1 + 1 = 2, you should hold firmly to
  your own view that 1 + 1 &gt; 2.
</p>
<p>
  In a modern, industrialized world, some families have always placed great
  importance on teaching their children to be quick and sharp. Some may look
  down on this kind of cleverness, or disapprove of it, but in truth, that
  keen intelligence springs from an attitude. These families do not treat
  sharp intelligence as an end in itself, but as something to put to use in
  life. The best of them never use their intelligence to talk others into
  doing things that harm their own interests for the cleverer party's gain.
  They earn money only in an intelligent way, building wealth without
  violating morality or the law.
</p>
<p>
  Below, let us look at exactly which aspects this intelligent way of raising
  children shows itself in.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p><strong>&#10051; Intelligence, Open and Aboveboard</strong></p>
<p>
  Such merchants have grown more and more intelligent and resourceful. Beyond
  their deep knowledge and the knocks they have taken out in the world, there
  is one thing that matters greatly: their attitude toward intelligence and
  resourcefulness. It cannot be denied that every country and every people
  has no shortage of intelligent individuals, but their attitudes toward
  intelligence differ. In these families, the attitude toward intelligence
  and resourcefulness is the same as the attitude toward money: they openly
  praise and admire the intelligence of others. And in this way, they
  themselves become intelligent too.
</p>
<p>
  In the family, parents constantly encourage their children to ask questions
  and to think actively, so as to enrich their knowledge and train their
  ability to solve problems. Parents generally do not become annoyed or angry
  when a child is mischievous or shows a streak of cunning. They believe that
  a child being mischievous or sly, as long as it does no harm to others, is
  still acceptable. But if it goes too far, the parents will take appropriate
  measures so the child takes responsibility and receives a reasonable
  punishment.
</p>
<p>
  <strong
    >&#10051; Treating Intelligence and Resourcefulness as a Necessity in
    Life</strong
  >
</p>
<p>
  To these families, being intelligent and resourceful is an ordinary thing.
  They hold that a clever, shrewd person does not deserve to be blamed; the
  one who can use their intelligence effectively is the one who truly has
  wisdom. If a person is extremely intelligent but does not know how to use
  it, then that intelligence is worthless. They admire intelligence of a
  practical kind, one that has no need of complicated schemes. Take, for
  instance, the chairman of the board in the example above: he gently lifted
  the price of a pound of copper from 35 cents to 3,500 dollars. That is
  intelligence that is simple, effective, and worthy of praise.
</p>
